*** Minimum requirements

1. linux based operating system (tested in Ubuntu 14 and Debian 9)
2. ROOT 6 (tested with 6.14/06). May need libroot-math-physics-dev (install using synaptic package manager or similar)
3. g++ compiler (tested with g++ 4.8.4)
4. git (tested with version 1.9.1


*** Installation instructions

1. Get the codes
cd to your preferred working directory
git clone https://gitlab.phy.anl.gov/dasago/music-simulator.git
git clone https://gitlab.phy.anl.gov/andes/physics-tools.git

2. Compile it (ignore all warnings but if there are errors send them to dasago@anl.gov)
cd physicstools
g++ -shared -fPIC EnergyLoss.cpp `root-config --cflags --glibs` -o EnergyLoss.so
g++ -shared -fPIC FourVector.cpp -o FourVector.so  
g++ -shared -fPIC Particle.cpp `root-config --cflags --glibs` -o Particle.so
root -l NuclideFinder.cpp++
.L SRIM_Table_Maker.cpp++
.q
cd ../music_simulator
git checkout fusion_evap
root -l MakeAll.C
.q

3. Test it
cd Examples/Fusion16C
root -l RunMusicSim_16C.C

If everything went well you should see two windows, one with a 2D plot of the MUSIC traces and
another one with a 3D view of the event.
